<subSubSection id="C32E54C81639FFD6B59EE65B6870CB3F" pageId="47" pageNumber="363" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8B07431639FFD6B59EE65B6A2EC8EA" blockId="47.[160,1155,1404,1603]" box="[160,375,1404,1430]" pageId="47" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B940DB511639FFD6B59EE65B6A2EC8EA" bold="true" box="[160,375,1404,1430]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="363">Geographic range</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B07431639FFD6B59EE6876870CB3F" blockId="47.[160,1155,1404,1603]" pageId="47" pageNumber="363">
A widespread invasive species originally described from 
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31639FFD6B616E6876806C8C4" box="[808,863,1440,1464]" name="India" pageId="47" pageNumber="363">India</collectingCountry>
and occurring in tropical and subtropical regions of the world (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB21639FFD6B76CE6E4685CC8A7" author="Wetterer JK" box="[594,773,1475,1499]" pageId="47" pageNumber="363" pagination="97 - 108" refId="ref21213" refString="Wetterer JK. 2009 b. Worldwide spread of the destroyer ant, Monomorium destructor (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Myrmecological News. 12: 97 - 108." type="journal article" year="2009">Wetterer 2009b</bibRefCitation>
), supposedly spread from central Asia west to north Africa (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB21639FFD6B4F5E6C1691DC882" author="Forel A" box="[459,580,1510,1534]" pageId="47" pageNumber="363" pagination="369 - 407" refId="ref19107" refString="Forel A. 1909. Etudes myrmecologiques en 1909. Fourmis de Barbarie et de Ceylan. Nidification des Polyrhachis. Bulletin de la Societe Vaudoise des Sciences Naturelles. 45: 369 - 407." type="journal article" year="1909">Forel 1909</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB21639FFD6B76CE6C16980C882" author="Sharaf MR" box="[594,729,1510,1534]" pageId="47" pageNumber="363" refId="ref20539" refString="Sharaf MR 2006. Taxonomic and ecological studies on family Formicidae (Order: Hymenoptera) in Egypt including some protectorates with a study of some insect fauna associated with ant species [unpublished thesis]. Cairo: Ain Shams University, Faculty of Science, Entomology Department; 340 pp." type="book" year="2006">Sharaf 2006</bibRefCitation>
), southern Europe (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB21639FFD6B684E6C16F11C882" author="Ruzsky M" box="[954,1096,1510,1534]" pageId="47" pageNumber="363" pagination="1 - 122" refId="ref20245" refString="Ruzsky M. 1907. Murav' i Rossii. (Formicariae Imperii Rossici.). Trudy Obshchestva Estestvoispytatelei pri Imperatorskom Kazanskom Universitete. 40: 1 - 122." type="journal article" year="1907">Ruzsky 1907</bibRefCitation>
) and the Arabian Peninsula (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB21639FFD6B49DE52F6928CB5C" author="Collingwood CA" box="[419,625,1544,1568]" pageId="47" pageNumber="363" pagination="230 - 302" refId="ref18149" refString="Collingwood CA. 1985. Hymenoptera: fam. Formicidae of Saudi Arabia. Fauna Saudi Arabia. 7: 230 - 302." type="journal article" year="1985">Collingwood 1985</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB21639FFD6B743E52F6893CB5C" author="Collingwood CA &amp; Agosti D" box="[637,970,1544,1568]" pageId="47" pageNumber="363" pagination="300 - 385" refId="ref18173" refString="Collingwood CA, Agosti D. 1996. Formicidae (Insecta: Hymenoptera) of Saudi Arabia (part 2). Fauna of Saudi Arabia. 15: 300 - 385." type="journal article" year="1996">Collingwood and Agosti 1996</bibRefCitation>
). In the 
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31639FFD6B119E52F6F0FCB5C" box="[1063,1110,1544,1568]" name="United States of America" pageId="47" pageNumber="363">USA</collectingCountry>
it is reported from Key West and Tampa (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB21639FFD6B777E50C6844CB3F" author="Deyrup M &amp; Davis L &amp; Cover S" box="[585,797,1579,1603]" pageId="47" pageNumber="363" pagination="293 - 325" refId="ref18446" refString="Deyrup M, Davis L, Cover S. 2000. Exotic ants in Florida. Trans Am Entomol Soc. 126: 293 - 325." type="journal article" year="2000">Deyrup et al. 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF4B57CB1626FFC9B59EE58A6AFBCB83" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5184345" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5184345" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5184345/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="364" startId="48.[160,225,1709,1732]" targetBox="[251,1065,142,1678]" targetPageId="48">
<paragraph id="8B8B07431626FFC9B59EE58A6AFBCB83" blockId="48.[160,1157,1709,1791]" pageId="48" pageNumber="364">
<emphasis id="B940DB511626FFC9B59EE58A6A50CBB8" bold="true" box="[160,265,1709,1732]" pageId="48" pageNumber="364">Figure 25.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C347CC01626FFC9B42FE58A6AA6CBB8" baseAuthorityName="Jerdon" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[273,511,1709,1732]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="364" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="destructor">
<emphasis id="B940DB511626FFC9B42FE58A6AA6CBB8" box="[273,511,1709,1732]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="364">Trichomyrmex destructor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. (a) Body in profile. (b) Head in full-face view, CASENT0746624, AntWeb.org, (Zach Lieberman). (c) Distribution map, blue circles from recent records, red circles from 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA57AB21626FFC9B59EE5CF6AC7CB83" author="Collingwood CA &amp; Pohl H &amp; Guesten R &amp; Wranik W &amp; Van Harten A" box="[160,414,1768,1791]" pageId="48" pageNumber="364" pagination="473 - 495" refId="ref18239" refString="Collingwood CA, Pohl H, Guesten R, Wranik W, Van Harten A. 2004. The ants (Insecta: Hymenoptera: Formicidae) of the Socotra Archipelago. Fauna of Arabia. 20: 473 - 495." type="journal article" year="2004">Collingwood et al. (2004)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="C32E54C81627FFC8B59EE3AB699CCCC0" pageId="49" pageNumber="365" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B8B07431627FFC8B59EE3AB694CCDDA" blockId="49.[160,1156,140,444]" box="[160,533,140,166]" pageId="49" pageNumber="365">
<emphasis id="B940DB511627FFC8B59EE3AB694CCDDA" bold="true" box="[160,533,140,166]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="365">Ecological and biological notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B07431627FFC8B59EE396699CCCC0" blockId="49.[160,1156,140,444]" pageId="49" pageNumber="365">
<taxonomicName id="4C347CC01627FFC8B59EE3966AF7CDB5" baseAuthorityName="Jerdon" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[160,430,177,201]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Trichomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="365" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="destructor">
<emphasis id="B940DB511627FFC8B59EE3966AF7CDB5" box="[160,430,177,201]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="365">Trichomyrmex destructor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the most successful invasive species on 
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31627FFC8B6DEE3966FD8CDB5" box="[992,1153,177,201]" name="Socotra Island" pageId="49" pageNumber="365">Socotra Island</collectingCountry>
, occupying diverse habitats. It was found nesting directly in soil under a rock. Several workers were found in leaf litter under 
<taxonomicName id="4C347CC01627FFC8B763E3D16861CC72" authority="eragrostis" box="[605,824,246,270]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Eragrostis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="49" pageNumber="365" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="eragrostis">
<emphasis id="B940DB511627FFC8B763E3D16861CC72" box="[605,824,246,270]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="365">Eragrostis eragrostis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) (
<taxonomicName id="4C347CC01627FFC8B651E3D1688BCC72" authorityName="Barnhart" authorityYear="1895" baseAuthorityName="R.Br." box="[879,978,246,270]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="49" pageNumber="365" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
), where the soil was dry and rich in organic material. Several individuals were nesting under a rock in very moist, compact, clay soil. A nest was found under the bark of a dead rotten log located on a mountainside where a small stream was draining a mountain crest surrounded by diverse plant communities. Another nest series was found in leaf litter under a tree of 
<taxonomicName id="4C347CC01627FFC8B46BE2836963CCC0" authority="Thunb" authorityName="Thunb" box="[341,570,420,444]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Moraceae" genus="Ficus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="49" pageNumber="365" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cordata">
<emphasis id="B940DB511627FFC8B46BE2836AB1CCC0" box="[341,488,420,444]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="365">Ficus cordata</emphasis>
Thunb
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C347CC01627FFC8B776E28369E2CCC0" box="[584,699,420,444]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Moraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="49" pageNumber="365" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Moraceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
